<title type="html"><![CDATA[Proposal to include &lt;di&gt;-like element]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/viewtopic.php?t=47&amp;p=254#p254"><![CDATA[
Of course CSS and JavaScript can be used to emphasise the grouping and act as if there really are different branches within de <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;dl&gt;</span> tree.<br />Form validation can be done as well with JavaScript in HTML 4. Still, HTML 5 will have some new features to make that easier and more intuitive, to make it better.<br /><br /><blockquote><div><cite>Cerbera wrote:</cite><br />I can understand that <span style="font-weight: bold">&lt;di&gt;</span> could make the markup more readable, sure. But prettifying the markup seems a rather extravagant reason to add a new element?<br /></div></blockquote><br />More extravagant than adding an element called <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;dialog&gt;</span> which is pretty much the same as <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;dl&gt;</span>? An attribute might have done the trick here.<br /><br />And what about <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;fieldset&gt;</span>s then? Shall we call those deprecated as well, since adding <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;legends&gt;</span> to a form already implies the start of a new group of form fields as well in the same manner as a <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;dt&gt;</span> does within a <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;dl&gt;</span>. Even more perhaps as only one <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;legend&gt;</span> is allowed per group which is not the case for <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;dt&gt;</span>s.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://forums.whatwg.org/bb3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=87">Sander Aarts</a> — Tue May 15, 2007 4:44 pm</p><hr />
